Dependent is marked with a gen.case marker which is derived from accusative. Personal pronouns used as possessors are marked with accusative case marker (see Overall 2007:199, 261). Construction is as follows: POSR-acc/gen POSSD-pers.pos.suf. There is also a possibility to mark possession by the following construction: POSR-pos POSSD (see Overall 2007:210).

Overall (2007:199): “In Aguaruna possession is normally head-marked (on the possessum) and dependent-marked (on the possessor), but there is also a nominal possessive marker that marks possessors without requiring any marking on the possessum. Nouns fall into two classes based on the marking they take as possessum. The first group, which I label “suffixing”, marks possession entirely with suffixes in all persons, while the second group (labelled “vowel-changing”) uses a combination of suffixes and root apophony in second person, and root apophony only in first plural and third persons. The classes are not distinguished when the possessor is first person singular; then all nouns are marked only with a suffix -hu. The marking forms two layers, one marking the noun as possessed and the second indexing the person of the possessor”.

Possessor is optional; if present, then the personal pronoun indicating the possessor occurs with the accusative marker. If absent, person and number of the possessor is indicated by the sufixes on the possessed noun (see Overall 2007:261).

Possessor is optional, if present them the personal pronoun indiatign the possessor occurs with the accusative marker. If absent, person and number of the possessor is indicated by the sufixes on the possessed noun (see Overall 2007:261).

There are two pairs of morphological number markers: -wako-ru ('-PL-F') and -wako-ro ('-PL-M'), and -nu-ru ('-PL-F')  and -nu-ro ('-PL-M'). The forms -wako-ru and -wako-ro are used only with nouns referring to humans. The morphemes marking gender (ߝru and ߝro) are obligatory and can't be omitted. When the plural marker occurs on the noun stem which is already marked for gender (the same gender markers ߝru and ߝro), the plural marker still occurs with the gender markers. The second pair of plural markers (-nu-ru and -nu-ro) can occur on nouns for animate and inanimate referents. Different from the other number marker, -nu is more often used with the gender markers but can be used without it. Facundes (2000:262) notes that it still needs to be verified if the dropping of the gender marker is restricted to nouns which already have a gender marker in their base.
'The occurence of plural markers is optional when plurality is already indicated somewhere else in the same phrasal construction'  (cf. Facundes 2000:262)

All nouns are either masc. or fem. for the purpose of cross-referencing with other elements within a syntactic construction. Within the NP, gender seems to be encoded on numeral 'one' used as a nominal modifier  and adnominal demonstratives. Majority of the nouns are not marked for gender, it is expressed on the verb by a cross-referencing suffix showing M/F gender of the object noun  (cf. Facundes 2000:218). Morphological gender marking on the noun itself is restricted to kinship terms and other nouns denoting humans; it is also used with the word for 'dog' (cf. Facundes 2000:222)

Numerals may precede or follow the head depending on whether the reference is definite or indefinite. Numerals occur before the noun when the reference is indefinite, and after the noun when reference is definite (cf. Frank 1990:31) (see Cubeo (Tucanoan), and Chibchan languages of Costa Rica where definiteness correlates with the order of adjective/noun).

Paul Frank (p.c. 15.04.2011): possessor-possessed is the typical order, while possessed possessor is also possible and not uncommon. 'In example involving ownership, the possessor phrase is much more likely to follow the possessed item' (Frank 1990:42).

Classifiers are not obligatory; if they occur they occur right after the classified noun. Plural is marked on the noun mainly by the suffix ߝdoge, or by some of its allomorphs with a restricted use: -e is the plural marker used nouns denoting animals, -mage is the plural marker used with kinship nouns, -ge occurs on pronouns (cf. Nonato 2008:50). Crowell (1979:223) notes that inanimate nouns can receive a plural marker -doge if the speaker wishes to make it clear that more than one item is involved. Nonato (2008:53) mentions that some nouns have to receive a singular marker ߝdü to signal singular reading.
Only animate nouns are pluralized regularly, inanimate nouns can receive a plural marker -doge if the speaker wishes to make it clear that more than one item is involved (cf. Crowell 1979:223).
It is not clear though if the same plural markers can have a collective meaning as well.

In possessive constructions with overt nominal possessor, the word order seems to be possessor following the possessed; while in constructions with pronominal possessor, the possessor precedes the possessed (cf. Danielsen 2007:126,168).

Modification within NP is not very common in general in Baure (cf. Danielsen 2007:168). The preference for a particular word order of adjective and head noun depends on the kind of adjective:  adjectives of 'class III: derived forms' which constitute the largest part of the adjective class are mainly post-nominal (13 cases out of 14); adjectives of 'absolute class II' (which do not get classifier incorporated, and whose forms remain unchanged) are predominantly adnominal (32 cases out of 50); adjectives of 'class I: right-bound roots' (denoting dimension, and used with classifiers) are postnominal (3 cases out of 3) (cf. Danielsen 2007:168).

Relative clauses are characterized by a nominalized predicate, and generally follow the noun (comparable to the behaviour of modifying adj-s of class III 'which are frequently nominalized forms, marked by -no 'nom1', one of the nominalizers used in relative clauses' (Danielsen 2007:171).

In narratives, examples with VOS word order is found esp. when human or animate argument is involved. For emphasis S precedes V, this is also the means of marking of the change of S (cf. Danielsen 2007:333). If S is expressed by a pronoun, the pronoun generally precedes the predicate: S-Pred-O.

In modifying constructions with adjectives only the last element of the NP is marked for plural. When adjective is used predicativly then both adjective and noun can be marked for plural (cf. Danielsen 2007:132). Danielsen (2007:168) notes that '[m]odification within an NP is not very common in Baure in general', they are considerably more often used predicatively (see statistics: Danielsen 2007:168).

See example (39) on p.131 of numeral+noun NP, where number is marked only at the phrase level. Danielsen (2007:168) notes that '[m]odification within an NP is not very common in Baure in general', they are considerably more often used predicatively (see statistics: Danielsen 2007:168). Numerals belong to the class I adjectives ('right-bound roots') and are used with classifiers. There are only three numerals, they have to occur with a classifier; numerals above three are borrowed from Spanish, these can receive cls as well. The root 'other' is also member of this class and also receives cls.  (cf. Danielsen 2007:159).

Adjectives of 'class III: derived forms' constitute the largest part of adjective class. They are derived from verbs and nouns by means of the nominalizer -no and/or with the attributive prefix ko- 'ATTR/with' or mo- 'PRIV/without'. Sakel 2003:52).

The plural can be marked by the clitic in or by reduplication of the nominal root. There are two types of reduplication in Mosetén: global reduplication and partial reduplication. Global reduplication appears in very few cases, and the use of the plural clitic in is preferred. Partial reduplication is used to express 'distributed plurality': to express that entities are distributed over a certain area (cf. Sakel 2003:66).

'Non-human objects are often represented as singular in number, as opposed to humans and higher animates. The latter includes animals which in the mythology appear in the shape of humans' (Sakel 2003:68). 'Things are only pluralised when there is a focus on the plurality - they don't have to be marked by the (nominal) plural marker. Yet, there is such marking in the verbal cross-reference ending' (J.Sakel, p.c. email 19.04.2011). When nouns are modified by a numeral, there is no plural marker (this is also the case for human nouns), e.g. paerae äwä 'two sons' (cf. Sakel 2003:68).

Feminine and masculine. Human females are in the fem.gender and human males are in the masculine gender; in most other cases the assignment of gender is arbitrary. Genders are inherent to nouns are only realized on other constituents on the NP (cf. Sakel 2003:69).

Verbal relative clauses tend to occur after the head noun; a number of copula relative clauses, notably demonstrative RC (there are no nominal demonstratives in Cavineña) and interrogative RC, only occur preposed to the head noun (cf. Guillaume 2008:406).

Plural marker is optional with all nouns. In case of plural NPs with overt plural marker, the plural marker is found cliticized to the property concept as it occurs after the head noun (e.g. cooking.pot big=PL 'cooking pots' (cf. Guillaume 2008:465)).
There are examples of [num-noun-PL] NPs (ex.13.78d), however it should not be considered as agreement; besides, plural markers are optional with all nouns (cf. Guillaume 2008:480).

Cavineña has only two types of demonstratives: adverbial demonstratives and pointing demonstratives, there are no specific nominal demonstratives (cf. Guillaume 2008:80). There are 2 strategies to compencate for the lack of nominal demonstratives: (1) to mark a pointing dem, which is a peripheral element, with the relative clause marker =ke. The resulting relative clauses then can be used as noun modifiers within an NP (preceding the head noun). (2) to use a pointing dem in apposition to an NP, i.e. without any further marking (cf. Guillaume 2008:621,622).

Cavineña has only two types of demonstratives: adverbial demonstratives and pointing demonstratives, there are no specific nominal demonstratives.  Both types of dem-s encode 3 distance degrees  (cf. Guillaume 2008:80). There are 2 strategies to compencate for the lack of nominal demonstratives: (1) to mark a pointing dem, which is a peripheral element, with the relative clause marker =ke. The resulting relative clauses then can be used as noun modifiers within an NP (preceding the head noun). (2) to use a pointing dem in apposition to an NP, i.e. without any further marking (cf. Guillaume 2008:621,622).

There are two different classes of adjectives in Cavineña: an open class of predicative adjectives and a closed class of attributive adjectives. Predicative adjectives function only as copula complements (and never as attributive modifers), but they are very often used attributively within (copula) relative clauses, while attributive adjectives function only as NP modifiers (and never predicatively) (cf. Guillaume 2008:61,465). Attributive adjectives constitute a closed class of 16 bare roots which belong to the following 4 semantic groups: dimension, age, color, and physical properties (cf. Guillaume 2008:73). Some of these adjectives are forms which partially overlap with predicative adjective forms for the same meaning. Predicative adjectives can express the same and other adjectival concepts (dimension, age, color, physical properties, human propensities, etc).

Comment from Antoine Guillaume (p.c. 14.10.2010): 'The only way to specify the gender of a noun (of a animal generally) is by juxtaposing the word deka 'male' or puna 'female' to the word.  But this is never obligatory and actually occurs very infrequently in my corpus, typically for chicken (takure deka 'rooster')'.

Guillaume (2008:409) reports a closed class of 100-150 members, which does not accept borrowed or derived terms. Hein van der Voort (p.c.) points out that these forms which are referred to by Guillaume (2008:409) as 'e-nouns' are in fact very similar to constructions in Kwaza, Movima and some other languages of the area, and are in fact classifiers which are obligatorily suffixed to the empty root 'e-' (Guillaume (2008:409) referres to e- as 'noun prefixes'). The majority of the forms which can be treated as classifiers (Hein van der Voort p.c.) 'have more than two syllables and can form independent phonological words even if they do not take affixes (whether the e-prefix or a derivational affix) or if they are not compounded with another root'. However, 5 forms are monosyllabic (Guillaume 2008:412)
Dual and plural forms of personal pronouns contain dual and plural markers tse (from =ekatse 'DL') and kwana or na (for 3person) (from  =kwana 'PL') (cf. Guillaume 2008:78).

'Relative clauses are either postnominal, or more commonly, appear in a noun phrase without any overt head noun. In the latter case, they can equally well be considered as noun phrases which happen to be headed by a nominalized verb. The nominalized verb is always clause final in the relative clause, and takes any case marking imposed by the independent clause. If the NP being modified by a relative clause is headed by an overt noun, both the head noun and the verb of the relative clause will then be case marked. This implies that a relative clause modifying an overt noun appears in an appositive structure'.  (Morse & Maxwell 1999:151).

The class of underived adjectives is very small. Many nominalized verbs serve the function of adjectives (Morse & Maxwell 1999:124). They most resemble nouns, however, noun and adj-s may be distinguished by the classifiers that appear (or fail to appear) on each (cf. Morse & Maxwell 1999:123,124).
Numeral for 'two' is an adjective, whereas the numeral for 'three' seems to be a verb (see p. 127,124).

Animate nouns have a different form of plural suffix (-wA) (cf. Morse & Maxwell 1999:74-77).

The demonstratives “occur preceding the head noun and before the numeral in the noun phrase. They take a noun classifier when preceding or replacing inanimate, countable nouns. They can and most frequently do occur without the noun” (Miller 1999:5).

'Numerals usually occur before the head noun, or follow the head noun and precede the classifier.' When numerals are in the same noun phrase with demonstratives, they follow the demonstrative. With animate nouns, the numerals often follow the head noun; the numerals carry the gender or class suffix that agrees with the noun.” (Miller 1999:4). See Miller (1999:46) for additional info.

“The descriptive modifier generally precedes the head noun in the NP. When it goes before the head, it is marked with a deverbalizer but not with a class or gender marker. It follows the head noun when a demonstrative, number [OK: numeral], or genitive precedes the nouns. Following the noun, the deverbalized modifier is inflected with the noun class or gender marker, or the noun is repeated if it does not have a separate class marker.” (Miller 1999:3).

The referential proclitic či precedes the head of the NP to indicate that the referent noun has already been mentioned or understood by the context (cf. Mortensen 1999:37). Also: when this referential proclitic precedes a verb, the action concerned is reciprocal. There is the dem.form mã- 'this, the' which occurs preceding a noun which has been mentioned in a given context if it is of any importance in the story.'Most participants and props are preceded by mã- only once in a discourse' (Mortensen 1999:135). The demonstrative hã- 'that' is anaphoric in reference and encodes thematic distance (cf. Mortensen 1999:136).

Dixon (2004:86) mentions that '[m]ore than half the clauses in Jarawara texts are intransitive', and only about 3% of transitive clauses have both A and O stated. In such cases, in about 85% of the time the A precedes the O and about 73% of the time the O precedes the A. The order is not fixes and grammatically not significant (cf. Dixon 2004:86).

NB: There is a closed class of 14 adjs. Two of these adjectives have distinct gender forms: bite/biti 'small' and one/owa 'another'. Besides this class of monomorphemic adjectives,  there is a small number of derived adj-s. Derived adj-s may function only as copula complements but not as modifiers within an NP (cf. Dixon 2004:337). Agreement within NP in Jarawara seems to be present only in possessive constructions: if 2 possessed nouns follow a 1/2 n.sg pronoun, each must be in a masc. form (see example p.340 + table 11.2). When a 1/2 n.sg pronoun is followed by a possessed noun and then an adjective, then the possessed noun is in masc. form but the adjective in in fem.form (see example p.341 + table 11.2). In possessive constructions: with alienable possession it is the possessed which determines the gender of an NP (for predicate agreement), and it is the possessor which determines the gender with inalienable possession (cf. Dixon 2004:280).
Native 'numbers'  are 1 and 2, other numbers are loans from Portuguese. They are verbs and seem to be used as predicates only  (cf. Dixon 2004:559).

Possessor is marked with alienably possessed nouns only (possessive marker is realized as a free (not bound) possessive morpheme, see also Hup); nominal possessor is simply juxtaposed to inalienably possessed nouns  (Dixon 2004:295)

In cases when the alienable possessor is a singular pronoun, the form looks as follows: 1sg o- plus kaa => oko 'my', 2sg ti- plus kaa => tika 'your (sg)', 3sg hina plus kaa => hinaka 'his/her' (Dixon 2004:296). In cases when the inalienable possessor in a singular pronoun, it gets prefixed to the possessed - with some nouns, while with other nouns the possessor is expressed by a free pronoun; plural pronouns are always free words (cf. Dixon 2004:77,325).
Possessor is marked with alienably possessed nouns only; nominal possessor is simply juxtaposed to inalienably possessed nouns  (Dixon 2004:295)

In Jarawara, a stance verb - rather than a copula- is used for location (cf. Dixon 2004:381). In Hup, predicate locatives similarly involve a stance verb or the neutral verb ni- 'be present, exist' (cf. Epps 2008:767).

There is a closed class of 14 adjectives; also there is a derivational process of limited productivity for deriving adjectives from stative verbs (Dixon 2004:75,335). 'Adjectives are very similar to possessed nouns in their grammatical properties' (p.75)
There are also verbs relating to dimension (cf. Dixon 2004:337).
There are also verbs relating to value, e.g. the word for 'good' is expressed by a verb -amosa- 'be good' (cf. Dixon 2004:336-7).
An example in Dixon (2004:339)

Number is not marked on the noun itself but by pronominal cross-referencing on the verb. The sg/nsg distinction in 3rd p pronouns only applies for animates; all inanimates have zero pronominal cross-referencing. However, the verbal suffix -rawa 'nsg.fem' is used with all types of fem.nouns, both animate and inanimate (cf. Dixon 2004:75,289). See p.75 for the related distinctions shown lexically.

NB: About 10 stance verbs have suppletive forms for sg, du, or pl. Number is not marked on the noun itself but by pronominal cross-referencing on the verb. The sg/nsg distinction in 3rd p pronouns only applies for animates; all inanimates have zero pronominal cross-referencing. However, the verbal suffix -rawa 'nsg.fem' is used with all types of fem.nouns, both animate and inanimate (cf. Dixon 2004:75). See p.75 for the related distinctions shown lexically.
There is no gender/sex distinction, though there is animacy distinction (see Dixon 2004:77)

Fem is an unmarked term form. Gender is not shown in the form of a noun but by agreement with other items, both within NP and outside NP. Nouns referring to humans have gender according to the sex of the referent; non-human animates have a fixed gender (~85% being masc) (cf. Dixon 2004:284). Within an NP gender is marked on the adjectives bite/biti 'small' and one/owa 'another' (they function both as adjectives and as nouns), the interrogative hibaka/hibake 'who' shows gender, and nominal demonstratives (e.g. haaha/haahi 'this') (cf. Dixon 2004:286).

Only within animate 3rd p pronouns. Inanimate 3rd p pronouns do not distinguish number (cf. Dixon 2004:77)

Kin terms, plant parts, human terms and some other nouns (for the list of nouns see Epps 2008:250) - these nouns are obligatorily possessed. They are typically preceded by a proper name, another kin term, or by a subject pronoun, i.e. a morphologically unmarked pronoun (cf. Epps 2008:234). Interestinly, and typologically very unusual, that animal body parts are treated as inalienably possessed, while human body parts are alienably possessed. Additionally, generic human nouns are in the set of obligatorily possessed nouns (cf. Epps 2008:233).

In Hup, in predicate locatives a stance verb or the neutral verb ni- 'be present, exist' is used, 'in addition to the predicative noun and locative postposition' (Epps 2008:767). (In Jarawara, similarly, a stance verb - rather than a copula- is used for location (cf. Dixon 2004:381).

Kinship terms, for instance, muj 'mother', papa 'pather', keke 'grandmother' etc., have to occur with the overt statement of the possessor (either a noun or possessive pronoun). They may occur without being determined by a possessive pronoun only in the syntactic function of a vocative (Laércio Bcelar, p.c. 22.03.2011). Further, there are nouns which occur with the neutral prefix i- (mainly denoting body parts, but interestingly not with parts of the body that can be trimmed or cut (hair, nails) or plucked (teeth) L.Bacelar, p.c.). These could have been regarded as inalienable nouns, or as nouns with the empty formative root i-. Similar phenomenon in Sabanê and some other languages of the region (cf. H. van der Voort 2009:366 (Possession, ed. B.McGregor), and H. van der Voort, p.c., referred to in Araujo 2004:103 (A grammar of Sabanê )).

Kinship terms, for instance, muj 'mother', papa 'pather', keke 'grandmother' etc., have to occur with the overt statement of the possessor (either a noun or possessive pronoun). They may occur without being determined by a possessive pronoun only in the syntactic function of a vocative (Laércio Bcelar, p.c. 22.03.2011). Further, there are nouns (mainly denoting body parts) which occur with the neutral prefix i-. These could have been regarded as inalienable nouns, or as nouns with the empty formative root i-. Similar phenomenon in Sabanê and some other languages of the region (cf. H. van der Voort 2009:366 (Possession, ed. B.McGregor), and H. van der Voort, p.c., referred to in Araujo 2004:103 (A grammar of Sabanê )).

In Kanoé, the specification of gender can optionally occur with 'oj' 3S and  'ojte' 3PP, with the posposition of the free forms 'ävo' for MASC and  'nake' FEM. It is not obligatory, but optional. Marking MASC  occurs with low frequency. Thus, if the speaker wants to avoid ambiguity, the most common is the marking FEM. However, if there are two distinct  referent genders related to the marking becomes obligatory in coordinated structure by juxtaposition: 'oj ävo oj nake' (Ele e ela, He and she) (L. Bacelar, p.c. email from 13.01.2011).

With alienably possessed nouns; with inalienably possessed nouns person markers are prefixed directly to the possessed noun.

With alienably possessed nouns: nominal possessor  receives a possessive/benefactive suffix -moki, or if nominal possessor is not realized then person markers receive a possessive/benefactive suffix -moki (not full person pronouns, but person markers). When a noun is modified by a numeral, the number marking is not obligatory with animate referents and often absent with inanimate referents. NB: Demonstrative form is a bound form in L. It can occur prefixed either to a noun, to a noun with a classifier, or to a classifier directly (cf. Telles 2002:195-197).
Native numerals are verbs, which occur with a classifier prefixed to the verbal root thus substituting the noun (cf. Telles 2002:191, 315-317).

NB: Property concepts are expressed by stative verbs in L. which occur with (require?) a classifier, resulting in a nominalization. Nouns to which classifier (attached to the verbal root) refers are not necessarily present. If present they can bear the same classifier marker (cf. Telles 2002:200-201). Certainty: ?

Numerals are expressed by stative verbs in L. which occur with a classifier. Nouns to which classifier refers may be left out. Telles (2002:190) gives examples when numeral stems are used without a classifier but occur directly with imperfective markers.

Adnominal demonstratives seem not to encode distance; no information found on adverbial demonstrative forms.

A reduced form of 3rd p. pronoun is used as a demonstrative ('hãj). The demonstrative form in L. does not encode any distance contrast (cf. Telles 2002:195). There is, however, a morpheme -te- which occurs suffixed on nouns and denotes 'distance of the referent', e.g. 'sih-te-'te [house-DIST-REF] 'house (which is far away)' (cf. Telles 2002:205).
Classifiers are not obligatory with demonstrative forms (cf. Telles 2002:196).
Certainty: ?

Possessive expressions have a construction of a compound. The 3rd person possessive prefix on the possessed is obligatory, possessor precedes the possessed, e.g. POSSR-3rd.p-POSSED (cf. Telles 2002:159)

Possessive expressions have a construction of a compound. The 3rd person possessive prefix on the possessed is obligatory, possessor precedes the possessed, e.g. POSSR-3rd.p-POSSED (cf. Telles 2002:159)

NB: Possession can also be expressed by unmarked personal pronouns preceding the possessed noun which does not receive any marking, e.g. [pers.pro POSSED]. Fleck (2003:252) notes that although possessive pronouns can be considered personal pronouns in the genetive case (they all end in -n), the pos.pronoun forms cannot be readily segmented as they are no correlates in the language for some of the forms without -n.

Nouns denoting kinship terms exept the terms for  'mother' and 'father' (cf. Fleck 2003:234). Interestingly, 'the absence of an overt possessor preceding a possessible kinship term (in a non-vocative sentence) is always interpreted as possessed by the second person' (Fleck 2003:234).

Fleck (2003:462) reports 58 adjective roots in Matsés. Matsés has a productive adjectivalization process, making the adjective class an open lexical class (which differs however from open classes as nouns and verbs by its relatively few number of roots). Dimension and speed notions are coded by adverbs instead of adjectives. Adjectives can be used as noun modifiers and as copular complements. 'In predicative constructions, adjectives must be clitized with one of a special subset of enclitics ('adjective-modifying enclitics'), which could be considered the adjectival inflections. These enclitics code intensification or de-intensification, large vs. small size (a sort of 'size-agreement comparable to adjectival gender agreement in Romance languages), and derogatory vs. complimentary' (Fleck 2003:462).
Most of property concepts encoding dimension are adverbs, plus there are 2 noun phrase enclitics (-mpi 'small', -dapa 'large') (cf. Fleck 2003:463).
NB: Age can also be encoded by several nouns (cf. Fleck 2003:463).
NB: Human propensity can also be expressed by many verbs (e.g. nëish 'get mad', cuishonque 'be happy') and nouns (e.g. shonto 'idiot', chishpi 'coward') (cf. Fleck 2003:463).
Adjectivalized nouns and verbs can only occur in predicative constructions, and not in attributive (cf. Fleck 2003:508). See also cf. Fleck (2003:466).

Plural enclitic -bo can optionally attach to any noun that refers to a human indicating either a set of people in a group, a catergory of people in general, or multiple people acting separately. In order to specify collective meaning, the verbal suffixes -cueded or -beded are used, optionally with or without the plural enclitic -bo (cf. Fleck 2003:273). The plural enclitic also occurs (less commonly) on non-human referents to specify a heterogeneous category (cf. Fleck 2003:272).

Plural enclitic -bo can optionally attach to any noun that refers to a human indicating either a set of people in a group, a catergory of people in general, or multiple people acting separately. In order to specify collective meaning, the verbal suffixes -cueded or -beded are used, optionally with or without the plural enclitic -bo (cf. Fleck 2003:273). The plural enclitic also occurs (less commonly) on non-human referents to specify a heterogeneous category (cf. Fleck 2003:272).

Probably the plural enclitic -bo can also indicate collectiveness. There are also verbal suffixes which specify collective semantics (the verbal suffix optionally occur with or without the plural enclitic -bo) (cf. Fleck 2003:273).

Historically 3rd p.pronoun was probably element a, nowadays it is not used in this function, 3rd person is left unmarked, whether singular or plural reference is meant. Therefore the Q answered as 'no number distinction'. Additionally, it can be mentioned that most personal pronouns in Matses (with exception of 2nd p. form mitso) cannot receive the plural/collective marker (-bo) which can be used on NPs to mark plurality. 'Personal pronouns are ambiguous with respect to plural vs. dual vs. singular, unless they occur with the pronoun-specific enclitic -ben 'alone/invain/for no reason', or one of the two quantitative postpositions daëdi 'both of' or tedi 'all of' (cf. Fleck 2003:243). However, demonstrative forms can be used as 3 p pronouns, which can occur with plural marker if plurality has to specified. Distal demonstrative forms are highly probably related to the element a which historically served as a 3rd p. pronoun (cf. Fleck 2003:260).

Copula is used in constructions with alienable nouns as predicates and personal pronouns as subjects. Copula is not used when subjects are expressed by proper names, or when nominal predicates are inalienably possessed nouns (thus occuring with a personal possessive prefix) (cf. Terraza 2009:66)

Classifiers are used in constructions with alienably possessed nouns only. There are 2 classifiers in Wichí:  lo is one is used only with referents denoting all kinds of animals (insects, reptiles, etc. incl.), whereas qa is used with all referents, whether they are inanimates, animates or human. There are two possible constructions with alienable nouns: (a) POSR cls POSSD, and (b) POSR pers.pos.pref-cls POSSD. Constructions with inalienable nouns do not require the use of a classifier. There are two possible constructions with inalienable nouns: (a) POSR POSSD, and (b) POSR pers.pos.pref-POSSD (cf. Terraza 2009:61,64,98). (Comment OK: the answers for Q 8.1. and 8.2. can be controversial, as it is hard to determine whether the head or the dependent is marked in this case. Answered as head-marked, since classifier (which can be regarded as the head) receives personal possessive prefixes, while possessor remains unmarked and can be omitted).

NB: In Wichí, classifiers are used in possessive constructions with alienable nouns. There are 2 classifiers:  lo is one is used only with referents denoting all kinds of animals (insects, reptiles, etc. incl.), whereas qa is used with all referents, whether they are inanimates, animates or human. Classifiers can occur as free morphemes or can receive a personal possessive prefix denoting the possessor (cf. Terraza 2009:61). See Mocoví where the same classifier lo is used with animals.

Collective marker is morphologically different from the plural markers in Wichí. Interestingly, plural and collective markers can co-occur. Terraza (2009:88) notes that in Toba (Guaycuruan), this is also the case, with the only difference that in Toba collective and plural can co-occur in certain contexts.

Classifiers are used in constructions with alienably possessed nouns only; inalienable nouns do not occur with a classifier. There are 2 classifiers in Wichí:  lo is one is used only with referents denoting all kinds of animals (insects, reptiles, etc. incl.), whereas qa is used with all referents, whether they are inanimates, animates or human. Classifiers can occur as free morphemes or can receive a personal possessive prefix denoting the possessor (cf. Terraza 2009:61).

Everett & Kern (1997:153) mention with regard to demonstratives in Wari': “There are three temporal demonstratives that distinguish how long the person or thing referred to has been absent: paca' 'that just occurred (always heard but never seen)', cara ne 'that recently absent', and cara pane 'that long absent'. It is hard to say whether ne and pane are actually part of the demonstrative. We have included them because they always accompany cara when used as a demonstrative (cara also occurs as a postverbal modifier, meaning 'always' or 'forever'). Ne and pane are sentence-final temporal particles ('recent past' and 'remote past' respectively).”

'Numerals appear in verbal position with the syntax of intransitive verbs' . “There is one compound verb that expresses the notion of cardinal numerals used as an attribute: xica' pe 'to be alone', used as 'one'. It is always used to express 'one', that is, the Portuguese numeral um is never used. There is another compound verb, tucu caracan 'to face each other', that used to be used as 'two' but is rarely used nowadays; rather the Portuguese numeral dois is used. Dois 'two' (masculine form of Portuguese 'two') is used irrespective of the gender of the noun it modifies. New numerals take the Portuguese form and occur as a simple verb' (Everett & Kern 1997:348).

In constructions with alienably possessed nouns, the most common construction in use is: [POSSD pers.pos.clitics POSSR], where 'pers.pos.clitics' are so-called Nominal Inflectional Clitics which inflect for person, number and gender of the possessor. Noun denoting the possessor can be omitted, in which case the possessive construction with alienable nouns looks as follows: [POSSD pers.pos.clitic], e.g. nanacam' nucun [fish:species poss:3sg.masc] 'his fish'. (See possessive constructions in Moseten, where possessive marker agreeing with the possessed occurs on the possessor and not on the possessed.) In constructions with inalienably possessed noun, the most common strategy to mark possession is to use possessive suffixes which encode person, number and gender of the possessor, e.g. xiri-con xijam [house-3sg.masc m:name] 'Xijam's house', or xiri-con [house-3sg.masc ] 'his house' (cf. Everett & Kern 1997:150,235).

“There is one compound verb that expresses the notion of cardinal numerals used as an attribute: xica' pe 'to be alone', used as 'one'. It is always used to express 'one', that is, the Portuguese numeral um is never used. There is another compound verb, tucu caracan 'to face each other', that used to be used as 'two' but is rarely used nowadays; rather the Portuguese numeral dois is used. Dois 'two' (masculine form of Portuguese 'two') is used irrespective of the gender of the noun it modifies. New numerals take the Portuguese form and occur as a simple verb. Numerals (both 'ON and loan numerals) appear in verbal position with the syntax of intransitive verbs.” (Everett & Kern 1997:347).

Pilagá has a set of class markers (some of these are used for derivational purposes), and a set of 6 classifiers. The classifiers can occur with count and mass nouns, they can stand by themselves or attach to demonstrative stems. Semantically, they can be divided into two groups: a) positional cls (vert.extended, horiz.extended, non-extended), and b) deictic cls (coming/proximal, going away/past, absent/distal) (cf. Vidal 2001:112-113).

Numerals are expressed by verbal roots which receive the attributive (nominalizing) prefix -i (have exactly the same construction as with verbal roots expressing property concepts) (cf. Girón 2008:297). Concluded from examples that the most common word order is NUM-NOUN, whereas NOUN-ADJ (despite that constructions with numerals and property concepts seem to be structurally similar).

Uncertain re the following information (to check): The word order POSSD POSSR is found in possessive constructions with alienable nouns, whereas possession of inalienable nouns is expressed by juxtaposition of two nouns with the order POSSR-POSSD (cf. Girón 2008:386).

Property concepts are mainly expressed by verbal roots which receive the attributive (nominalizing) prefix -i (cf. Girón 2008:167,233) which is used to mark relative clauses (cg. Girón 2008:407). Numerals are expressed by verbal roots which receive the attributive (nominalizing) prefix -i (have exactly the same construction as with verbal roots expressing property concepts) (cf. Girón 2008:297). Concluded from examples that the most common word order is NOUN-ADJ, whereas NUM-NOUN (despite that constructions with numerals and property concepts seem to be structurally similar).

The attributive (nominalizing) prefix -i (which occurs on verbal roots to form attributives) is the morpheme to marks relative clauses. It can also be used to mark complement and adverbial clauses (cf. Girón 2008:405).
Property concpts are mainly expressed by verbal roots which receive the attributive (nominalizing) prefix -i (cf. Girón 2008:167,233).

Concluded from available examples that there is agreement in number between head noun and numeral modifier: both constituents receive a plural marker (cf. Girón 2008:448,386); however, examples on p.402,372,389 with inanimate nouns modified by a numeral show no agreement and the numeral does not carry the attributive prefix -i which normally occurs on numerals (numerals are expressed by verbal roots, have exactly the same construction as with verbal roots expressing property concepts) (cf. Girón 2008:297).

Concluded from available examples that there is agreement in number between head noun and numeral modifier: both constituents receive a plural marker (cf. Girón 2008:448,386); however, example on p.402,372,389 with inanimate nouns modified by a numeral show no agreement and the numeral does not carry the attributive prefix -i which normally occurs on numerals (numerals are expressed by verbal roots, have exactly the same construction as with verbal roots expressing property concepts) (cf. Girón 2008:297).
There are indefinite pronouns (sing and plural form) which seem to be used as indefinite markers (cf. Girón 2008:171).
There are definite pronouns (sing and plural form) which seem to be used as definite markers, the definite pronouns do not encode a distance contrast (cf. Girón 2008:171).
NB: adverbial demonstratives can encode visible vs. non-visible distinction (cf. Girón 2008:175).

'There is a strong tendency to have either a subject or object present, but not both'.Out of 714 sentences having transitive verbs, only 99 have both S and O (about 12%). 'Of these 99 cases, only 48 have SOV order.The total number of sentences in the corpus that are not consistent with SOV order is 160 (about 12%)'. Weber (1996:16) gives the following statistics: Out of 1309 sentences: intransitive sentences: 53% of the sentences with subject present (76% word order SV, 24% word order VS). Transitive sentences: 31% of the sentences with subject present (75% word order SV, 68% word order OV); 69% of the sentences with subject absent (71% word order OV). 'There is a strong tendency to have either a subject or object present, but not both.' (cf. Weber (1996:16) for more details).

Number marking on the noun is not obligatory when it is modified by a numeral (cf. Cole 1982:128).
When a demonstrative is used as an attributive modifier of a plural noun, then it does not take plural number or case marker (cf. Cole 1982:133).
Demonstrative forms kay 'prox' and chay 'dist' are used for inaminate referents, whereas the 3rd pronoun pay '3sg' is employed for animates.

Demonstratives can occur with the same plural marker -kuna as other nominals (cf. Cole 1982:132). However, if a dem occurs with the number marker, the head nominal is not present (Pieter Muysken, p.c.) e.g. 'those (ones)'.
Dem-s used pronominally can take the same markers as nouns in that position

Copula is usually omitted when the verb is in the present tense, third person, and not bearing aspect. In other cases the use of copula is obligatory (cf. Cole 1982:67). The Q is answered as 'no' since here only present tense clauses are taken into accound and the obligatorily used copulas.
Cole (1982:115) mentions that '[t]here is no marking for possessed nominals in IQ. The possessive suffixes found in non-northern Quechua have been lost in Ecuador'.

The same possessive marker -paj is used for both nouns and pronouns denoting possessor. In the 1p sg/pl, the possessive marker is usually omitted on possessive adjectives, but is obligatorily retained on possessive pronouns (e.g. 'that house is mine/ours') (cf. Cole 1982:115).

Copula is usually omitted when the verb is in the present tense, third person, and not bearing aspect. In other cases the use of copula is obligatory (cf. Cole 1982:67). The Q is answered as 'no' since here only present tense clauses are taken into accound and the obligatorily used copulas.

Araujo (2004:102) notes that '[a]lienability is not morphologically distinct in Sabanê', while this distinction is widespread in Nambikwaran languages. Inanlienable nouns are frequently marked by the prefix a- in those languages. In Sabanê, all nouns referring to human body parts and animal parts begin with the vowel i or a; on this fact there are several suggestions: possible vestiges of an inalienability morphemes in Proto-Nambikwara (J.Costa, p.c., referred to in Araujo 2004:102);  an areal feature (H. van der Voort, p.c., referred to in Araujo 2004:103) (cf. Araujo 2004:102).

With alienably possessed nouns the possessive constructions look as follows: [POSSR {poss.clitic 'e'} POSSD] or [POSSR POSSD {poss.clitic 'e'}], where clitic 'e' may optionally precede or follow the possessed with no change in meaning. In cases of pronominal possessor the construction with alienably nouns is as follows: [pos.pronoun POSSD] (for 1st and 2nd person possessor) and [3rd personal pronoun {poss.clitic 'e'} POSSD] or [3rd personal pronoun POSSD {poss.clitic 'e'}] (for 3rd person possessor). In possessive constructions with kinship terms (inalienably possessed nouns), the construction is similar except that the poss.clitic 'e' always follows the kinship term and is preceded by an additional suffix which is phonologically determined. Possession of a body part is indicated either a personal or a possessive pronoun preceding the body part (cf. (Gómez 1990:52-56).

Plural of nouns denoting human and animate referents is formed by postposing the reduced form of the 3rd person plural animate pronoun /pIk/. Nouns denoting plants and inanimate objects usually take the partitive-collective suffix -k to mark plural (cf. Gómez 1990:79-80). E.g.: ~canam pIk [Yanam AN.PL] 'Yanam people', carekep mamo-k [two eye-INAN.PL] 'two eyes' (cf. Gómez 1990:79,74). [Comment: compare with Movima where plural marking is done by so-called referential elements].

Plural of nouns denoting human and animate referents is formed by postposing the reduced form of the 3rd person plural animate pronoun /pIk/. Nouns denoting plants and inanimate objects usually take the partitive-collective suffix -k to mark plural (cf. Gómez 1990:79-80). The co-occurrence of the partitive-collective suffix with a numeral is optional (cf. Gómez 1990:122). Certainty: ?

Only with animate nouns. The reduced forms of 3rd person dual (and plural) animate pronouns function to dualize (and pluralize) animate nouns and pronouns; the inanimate nouns can be only pluralized by the partitive-collective suffix -k (cf. Gómez 1990:49).

As there is no gender marking in SK, a systematic way to indicate male vs. female distinction in (a) humans: to use nouns ainbo 'woman' or benbo 'man' as modifiers, (b) in animals: to use nouns awin 'wife' or bene 'husband'; these forms are also used with a couple of plants. 'Specifier articles are homonymous with free third person pronouns, with one difference: unlike third person pronouns, articles do not have double plural marking for feminine forms and can combine with classifiers'. The articles occur preceding the noun, and they can be used anaphorically as heads of the noun phrases. Articles are never used when the noun is modified by a demonstrative, the gestural deictic khi, the distributive individualiser napada, the general indefinite pa:-, with numerals, or with quantifiers. (Aikhenvald 2003:204).
Prox. dem-s refer to objects which are close to S, to H, or both; distal dem-s are used to refer to objects far away from either, or from both (cf. Aikhenvald 2003:206).
There are 3 dem-s: proximate, distal, and proximate emphatic (cf. Aikhenvald 2003:105,206).

Proximate and distal dem-s can occur with classifiers, e.g. in order to focus on/specify the head noun for shape and form (only inanimate nouns) and for sex (animate nouns). There is another set of prox. dem-s which distinguish fem and masc, and cannot take clfs (cf. Aikhenvald 2003:207).

It is mentioned that not all consultants like the use of demonstratives as modifiers and prefer the use of dem-s as pronominal forms. When dem-s are used as modifiers, the masculine and feminine demonstrative forms can freely substitute for each other, with the masculine form used more often (cf. Guirardello 1999:30). No example with plural dem-s as modifiers are found; it can be speculated that modifying dem.plural forms will be used with nouns denoting plural animate entities (as nominal plural marker wan is used with animate nouns only), however, no data are available.

In constructions with inalienably possessed nouns, the possessor is juxtaposed to the possessed with no marking (word order: posser-possed) (cf. Guirardello 1999:17)

In constructions with inalienably possessed nouns: there are the following possibilities of possession marking. (i) with body parts and intimate objects (clothing, adornments, hammocks, shadows, homes, villages, names, pets, etc.), in case the possessor is either 1st or 2nd person sg or pl, the personal pronoun occurs before the possessed noun without any extra morphology. In case the possessor refers to a 3rd person sg or pl, there is an additional alternative construction in use: the noun denoting the possessed receives the possive suffix -ake. (ii) With kinship terms the situation is similar but slightly more complicated: if possessor refers to 1, 2, or 3rd person sg or pl possessor expressed by a personal pronoun can occur with no extra marking before the possessed. There is similarly an additional alternative construction when the possessor is a 3p. Namely: with 3p.sg the prefix tsi-/t- is used; with 3p.pl the suffix -ake is used (the same suffix as with body parts) (cf. Guirardel

In constructions with alienably possessed nouns, the possessor receives a poss. marker -k(a)te. With inalienably possessed nouns, the possessor is juxtaposed to the possessed with no marking (word order: posser-possed) (cf. Guirardello 1999:17)
In possessive constructions with animals as pets (rather than food, etc) the word aton 'pet' is required, 'which itself is inalienable possessed in the same way as body parts' (Guirardello 1999:77).

Plural morpheme wan. 'The pluralizers occur in an NP after the element they modify (noun, pronoun) but if there is no head noun, the pluralizer then stands by itself in the NP' (Guirardello 1999:55).

See note. Guirardello (1999:56) mentions that the plural marker is used only with animate referents, its use with inanimates is regarded ungrammatical. There is, however, an other factor which plays a role: with Dative NPs, the plural marker or the collective marker is required with human nouns, and seems to be optional with non-human animates (the presence of a quantifier or a numeral would be enough to give a non-singular meaning). With inanimate nouns the use of the plural morpheme is not possible (collective marker can be used) (cf. Guirardello 1999:58-61).
There is the noun paine (often reduced to pa) expressing the collective meaning, e.g. axos paine/pa 'collective of children (i.e. all the children in the village)' (cf. Guirardello 1999:56).

postposition ke can be used to add extra (adjunct) arguments to the verb that are not lexically specified. Semantically, this can have the effect of increasing the valency of the verb (by including a patientive argument), but the same strategy is used for a variety of argument types.  However, in cases where other postpositions can apply (e.g. goal/location), ke-marked arguments imply a more 'close relation to the verb'

Demonstratives, numerals, and possessor obligatorily occur in prenominal position. Most relative clauses (which are nominalizations) occur in prenominal position, while most property concepts occur in postnominal position (cf. Olawsky 2006:329-330).

NB: There are no underived adjectives; the words which have function usually assigned to adjectives can be devided into noun-like and verb-like. Therefore, the position is not homogeneous: some occur only postnominally (this is the unmarked variant), while others can occur prenominally and postnominally (cf. Olawsky 2006:308).

NB: When a noun is modified by a numeral, it can optionally be marked for plural. It is more common to mark the noun in combination with a numeral for plural if it refers to a human. In contrast, if the noun modified by a numeral does not refer to a human, it is unlikely to be marked for plural (cf. Olawsky 2006:367).

See examples Olawsky (2006:357,369). Demonstrativesdo not exhibit any number agreement within the NP. Demonstratives can occur with a plural marker, however it occurs only in the contexts when they are nominal heads themselves (cf. Olawsky 2006:369).

Olawsky (2006:216) notes that 'one could relate the three demonstratives with first, second, and third person respectively.' kaa 'this' has some degree of phonological similarity with kanu 'I'; the similarity between nii 'that' and ii 'you' is more subtle (different onset), taa 'that over there' and aka 'he/she/it' have even less in common (Olawsky 2006:216).

Adverbial demonstrative are composed of demonstrative base + locative suffix (cf. Olawsky 2006:176). Adverbial demonstratives can express a large variety of meanings: in sight vs. out of sight, directional, locational, punctual vs. non-punctual (cf. Olawsky 2006:224).

NB: There are several possessive constructions possible in NP in Urarina. Simple juxtaposition is the default case where two nouns (of any type) are involved. Such construction is also common when possessor is not expressed by a overt noun and when possessor refers to 1st or 2nd person. In that case an unmarked personal pronoun is used to express the possessor. In cases when possessor is not overtly expressed and refers to the 3rd person, the most common construction is with the use of possessive marker raj + POSSD (the possessive marker raj can occur in 2 different contexts: (a) as an optional marker between possessor and possessum, and (b) as a substitute for the 3rd person pronoun in possessor function) (cf. Olawsky 2006:333,340). Among possible strategies to mark possession, the construction [proclitic-POSSD] can be used instead of free personal pronouns. Nouns which are only marked with proclitics are typical of the traditional language, they  usually occur with formerly inalienab

Olawsky (2006:350,354) notes that Urarina might had inalienably possessed nouns at an earlier stage, but the feature has been largely lost over time. There are some some traces of inalienability: nouns denoting body parts, kinship terms, some human attributes and a few abstract nouns can occur with a possessive proclitic marking possession instead of free personal pronoun (the use of proclitics or free pronouns are both acceptable).

There is only one demonstrative form which attaches to the end of the nominal string. This form is more a specificatin device than a deictic one with a basic function to single out a particular object from the rest. However, this form tends to be used more often in reference to objects or people who are somewhat removed from the the location of the speaker. No corresponding demonstrative form with a proximate meaning has been found (Eberhard 2009:343-4).

Demonstrative form can be used with the 3rd person pronoun in order to refer to any nominal meaning 'that one that I am referring to' (cf. Eberhard 2009:343). However, the form is an affix and cannot be used by itself for pronominal function. Therefore answered as n/a.

Three forms of adverbial demonstratives (?) are mentioned in the grammar: one for proximal use and two for distal use; the distal forms have a visibility distinction (seen vs. unseen) (cf. Eberhard 2009:349). Certainty: ?

Body parts fall under inalienable possession. In isolated speech, the possessive marker for body parts is always the first person plural form /nũsa-/. 'Even when referring to their own body in connected speech, the Mamaindê will often revert to the  /nũsa-/ form.' (Eberhard 2009:329).

Classifiers function much like adjectives in M. (cf. Eberhard 2009:330). Typical adjectival qualities are expressed by verbs. These take the same morphology as verbs and behave like intransitive verbs in the language. Such verbal roots are not found on their own to modify a noun (Eberhard 2009:364).
Numerals can occur with so-called 'final nominal suffix' and they can occur with inflectional verb morphology when used as predicates (e.g. 'my grandchildren are two').
The plural suffix is used only when the speaker wants to emphasize plurality, both with animate and inanimate referents.

Gender can be specified by the female gender marker -ta, if gender needs to be highlighted (Eberhard 2009:358).

There is an affix -ta, which is used to mark the female gender, the male gender being unmarked. When used in reference to humans, the female marker typically attaches to the 'nimal/human' classifier. When it is not preceded by the animate classifier, the marker can take various senses: to specify a nominal as being a mother, or as being large, or as being dangerous (Eberhard 2009:340).

Eberhard (2009:330) notes that classifiers is a crucial component in the morphology of Nambikwaran languages. Mamaindê has the largest set of classifiers (24) among the N. languages. There is a small set of classifiers which can also function as noun roots. These take noun affixation as any noun, do not requiring any preceding nominal (Eberhard 2009:335).
NB: classifiers are not used in constructions with numerals. However, if a numeral stands without a noun it may occur with a classifier (cf. Eberhard 2009:502).
There is only one demonstrative form in the language. This form is affixed at the end of the nominal string, classifiers are found closer to the root (cf. Eberhard 2009:343,327). Certainty: ?
Classifiers on verbs are the most common method of  verb nominalization (cf. Eberhard 2009:337).
Plurality can be specified by the plural marker if plurality needs to be highlighted (Eberhard 2009:356).
